|''[[The Laundromat (film)|The Laundromat]]''||41% (5.53/10 average rating) (143 reviews)\n|57 (35 reviews)\n|{{N/A}}\n|{{N/A}}\n|{{N/A}}\n|}\nAs of 2018, Soderbergh's entire feature filmography has grossed over [[United States dollar|US$]]2.2&nbsp;billion worldwide in sales.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/people/chart/?view=Director&id=stevensoderbergh.htm|title=Steven Soderbergh Movie Box Office Results|website=www.boxofficemojo.com|language=en|access-date=2018-04-13}}</ref> His entire [[Ocean's (film series)|''Ocean's'' trilogy]] was named among the \"75 Best Heist Movies of All Time\" by [[Rotten Tomatoes]].<ref name=\":52\"/> His film ''Out of Sight'' was listed as one of the best movies of the 1990s by ''[[Rolling Stone]]''.<ref name=\":12\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* [[Sharon Waxman|Waxman, Sharon]] (2005). ''Rebels on the Backlot: Six Maverick Directors and How They Conquered the Hollywood Studio System''. New York: [[HarperCollins|HarperEntertainment]]. {{ISBN|9780060540173}}.\n* deWaard, Andrew, and R. Colin Tait (2013). ''The Cinema of Steven Soderbergh: Indie Sex, Corporate Lies, and Digital Videotape''. New York: Wallflower/[[Columbia University Press]].\n* Baker, Aaron (2011). ''Steven Soderbergh''. Urbana: [[University of Illinois Press]].\n* Gallagher, Mark (2013). ''Another Steven Soderbergh Experience: Authorship and Contemporary Hollywood''. Austin: [[University of Texas Press]].\n* Wood, Jason (2002). ''Steven Soderbergh''. Harpenden, UK: [[The Pocket Essentials|Pocket Essentials]].\n* Palmer, R. Barton, and Steven Sanders (2011). ''The Philosophy of Steven Soderbergh''. Lexington: [[University Press of Kentucky]].\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{Main|Steven Soderbergh bibliography}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons}}\n*{{IMDb name|0001752|Steven Soderbergh}}\n*{{iobdb name|43812}}\n*[http://www.lib.berkeley.edu/MRC/soderbergh.html Steven Soderbergh Bibliography] (via UC Berkeley)\n*[http://www.upress.state.ms.us/catalog/spring2002/steven_soderbergh.html Steven Soderbergh: Interviews]\n\n{{Steven Soderbergh|state=expanded}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for Steven Soderbergh\n|list =\n{{AcademyAwardBestDirector 1981-2000}}\n{{Broadcast Film Critics Association Award for Best Director}}\n{{DirectorsGuildofAmericaAwardMiniseriesorTVFilm}}\n{{EmmyAward MiniseriesDirector 2001\u20132025}}\n{{IndependentAwardforBestDirector}}\n{{Los Angeles Film Critics Association Award for Best Director}}\n{{National Society of Film Critics Award for Best Director}}\n{{Satellite Award Best Director}}\n{{Vancouver Film Critics Circle Award for Best Director}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Soderbergh, Steven}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:American atheists]]\n[[Category:American cinematographers]]\n[[Category:American documentary film producers]]\n[[Category:American documentary filmmakers]]\n[[Category:American film directors]]\n[[Category:American film producers]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Swedish descent]]\n[[Category:Best Directing Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Directors Guild of America Award winners]]\n[[Category:Directors of Palme d'Or winners]]\n[[Category:English-language film directors]]\n[[Category:Independent Spirit Award for Best Director winners]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Louisiana State University Laboratory School alumni]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Atlanta]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Baton Rouge, Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Writers from Atlanta]]\n[[Category:Writers from Baton Rouge, Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Writers from Charlottesville, Virginia]]\n", "name_user": "PaqqMann", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e1998\u20132008: reemergence and Ocean's trilogy:corrected 2 words.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steven_Soderbergh"}
{"title_page": "Immunogenetics", "text_new": "{{For|the journal|Immunogenetics (journal)}}\n{{unreferenced|date=August 2014}}\n\n'''Immunogenetics''' or '''immungenetics''' is the branch of [[medical genetics]] that explores the relationship between the [[immune system]] and [[genetics]].\n\nAutoimmune diseases, such as type 1 diabetes, are complex genetic traits which result from defects in the immune system. Identification of genes defining the immune defects may identify new target genes for therapeutic approaches. Alternatively, genetic variations can also help to define the immunological pathway leading to disease.\n\n==Origin==\nIts origin is usually attributed to [[Edward Jenner]], who discovered in 1796 that [[cowpox]], or vaccinia, induced protection against human [[smallpox]].\nIt took two centuries before the [[World Health Organization]] announced in 1979 that smallpox had been [[eradication of smallpox|eradicated]].\n\nThe term immunogenetics is based on the two words [[immunology]] and [[genetics]], and is defined as \"a sub discipline of genetics which deals with the genetic basis of the immune response (immunity)\" according to MeSH.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/mesh/68007125|title=Immunogenetics - MeSH - NCBI|website=www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nGenetics (based on Greek \u03b3\u03b5\u03bd\u03b5\u03ac ''gene\u00e1'' \"descent\" and \u03b3\u03ad\u03bd\u03b5\u03c3\u03b9\u03c2 ''g\u00e9nesis'' \"origin\")<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.etymonline.com/word/genetic|title=genetic {{!}} Origin and meaning of genetic by Online Etymology Dictionary|website=www.etymonline.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> is the science researching the transfer of characteristics from one generation to the next. The genes of an organism (strands of DNA) and the transfer of genes from the parent to the child generation of an organism in the scope of possible variations are the basis of genetics.\n\nImmunology deals with the biological and biochemical basis for the body's defense against germs (such as [[bacteria]], [[virus]]es, and [[Mycosis|fungi]]), as well as against foreign agents such as biological toxins and environmental pollutants, and failures and malfunctions of these defense mechanisms. Apart from these external effects on the organism, there are also defense reactions regarding the body's own cells, e.g. in the scope of the bodily reactions on cancer and the lacking reaction of a body on healthy cells in the scope of an immune-mediated disease. Hence, immunology is a sub-category of [[biology]].\n\nThe term immunogenetics comprises all processes of an organism, which are, on the one hand, controlled and influenced by the genes of the organism, and are, on the other hand, significant with regard to the immunological defense reactions of the organism.\n\n==History==\n\nThe medical history of [[immunology]] and the [[immune system]] dates back to the 19th century. However, the prevention and early defense of diseases was an essential task for all shamans, medicine men and early \"doctors\" during the entire human evolution. The first Nobel Prize in the field of immunogenetics was awarded to [[Baruj Benacerraf]], [[Jean Dausset]] and [[George Davis Snell]] in 1980 for discovering genetically determined cellular surface structures, which control immunological reactions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nobelprize.org/prizes/medicine/1980/summary/|title=The Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine 1980|website=NobelPrize.org|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n==Current research fields==\nSince 1972,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ashi-hla.org/page/ashi_history|title=ASHI History - American Society for Histocompatibility and Immunogenetics|website=www.ashi-hla.org|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> numerous H&I (histocompatibility and immunogenetics) organizations have be founded specializing in research activities on a large number of different questions in immunogenetics. Both the acceleration of and the decreasing costs for the sequencing of the genes have resulted in a more intensive research of both academic and commercial working groups. Current research topics particularly deal with forecasts on the course of diseases and therapy recommendations due to genetic dispositions and how these dispositions can be affected by agents (gene therapy).\n\nA special focus is often laid on the forecast regarding and therapy of genetically based [[autoimmune disease]]s, which include all diseases caused by an extreme reaction of the immune system against the body's own tissue. By mistake, the immune system recognizes the body's own tissue as a foreign object which is to be fought. This can result in serious inflammatory reactions which may permanently damage the respective organs. Autoimmune diseases, the outbreak and/or course of which can be visible in the individual genome of the organism, include [[multiple sclerosis]], [[diabetes type I]], [[rheumatoid arthritis]] and [[Crohn's disease]]. As for multiple sclerosis, an article in the journal ''Nature'' dated May 2010<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.4016/19108.01|title=Neil Miller on \u201cGenome, epigenome and RNA sequences of monozygotic twins discordant for multiple sclerosis\u201d|date=2010-07-06|website=SciVee|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> showed that this autoimmune disease is not caused by a genetic variation but the course and the treatability are considerably influenced by genetic dispositions. This research was based on analyzing three monovular pairs of twins, of which one twin has contracted multiple sclerosis whereas the other one has not.\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Histocompatibility]]\n* [[American Society for Histocompatibility and Immunogenetics]]\n* [[European Federation for Immunogenetics]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110210192027/http://www.ebi.ac.uk/imgt/ IMGT Databases at the European Bioinformatics Institute]\n* [http://www.womenshealth.gov/faq/autoimmune-diseases.cfm FAQ on autoimmune diseases by US Department for Health and Human Services]\n* [http://www.genome.gov/20019523 Homepage of the National Genome association studies]\n\n{{Genetics |expanded}}\n\n[[Category:Medical genetics]]\n[[Category:Branches of immunology]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the journal|Immunogenetics (journal)}}\n{{unreferenced|date=August 2014}}\n\n'''Immunogenetics''' or '''immungenetics''' is the branch of [[medical genetics]] that explores the relationship between the [[immune system]] and [[genetics]].\n\nAutoimmune diseases, such as type 1 diabetes, are complex genetic traits which result from defects in the immune system. Identification of genes defining the immune defects may identify new target genes for therapeutic approaches. Alternatively, genetic variations can also help to define the immunological pathway leading to disease.\n\n==Origin==\nIts origin is usually attributed to [[Edward Jenner]], who discovered in 1796 that [[cowpox]], or vaccinia, induced protection against human [[smallpox]].\nIt took two centuries before the [[World Health Organization]] announced in 1979 that smallpox had been [[eradication of smallpox|eradicated]].\n\nThe term immunogenetics is based on the two words [[immunology]] and [[genetics]], and is defined as \"a sub-category of genetics focussing on the genetic basis of the immune reaction\" according to MeSH.\nGenetics (based on Greek \u03b3\u03b5\u03bd\u03b5\u03ac ''gene\u00e1'' \"descent\" and \u03b3\u03ad\u03bd\u03b5\u03c3\u03b9\u03c2 ''g\u00e9nesis'' \"origin\") is the science researching the transfer of characteristics from one generation to the next. The genes of an organism (strands of DNA) and the transfer of genes from the parent to the child generation of an organism in the scope of possible variations are the basis of genetics.\n\nImmunology deals with the biological and biochemical basis for the body's defense against germs (such as [[bacteria]], [[virus]]es, and [[Mycosis|fungi]]), as well as against foreign agents such as biological toxins and environmental pollutants, and failures and malfunctions of these defence mechanisms. Apart from these external effects on the organism, there are also defence reactions regarding the body's own cells, e.g. in the scope of the bodily reactions on cancer and the lacking reaction of a body on healthy cells in the scope of an immune-mediated disease. Hence, immunology is a sub-category of [[biology]].\n\nThe term immunogenetics comprises all processes of an organism, which are, on the one hand, controlled and influenced by the genes of the organism, and are, on the other hand, significant with regard to the immunological defence reactions of the organism.\n\n==History==\n\nThe medical history of [[immunology]] and the [[immune system]] dates back to the 19th century. However, the prevention and early defence of diseases was an essential task for all shamans, medicine men and early \"doctors\" during the entire human evolution. The first Nobel Prize in the field of immunogenetics was awarded to [[Baruj Benacerraf]], [[Jean Dausset]] and [[George Davis Snell]] in 1980 for discovering genetically determined cellular surface structures, which control immunological reactions.\n\n==Current research fields==\nIn the last 20 years,{{When|date=September 2012}} research activities focussed on a large number of different questions in immunogenetics. Both the acceleration of and the decreasing costs for the sequencing of the genes have resulted in a more intensive research of both academic and commercial working groups. Current research topics particularly deal with forecasts on the course of diseases and therapy recommendations due to genetic dispositions and how these dispositions can be affected by agents (gene therapy).\n\nA special focus is often laid on the forecast regarding and therapy of genetically based [[autoimmune disease]]s, which include all diseases caused by an extreme reaction of the immune system against the body's own tissue. By mistake, the immune system recognises the body's own tissue as a foreign object which is to be fought. This can result in serious inflammatory reactions which may permanently damage the respective organs. Autoimmune diseases, the outbreak and/or course of which can be visible in the individual genome of the organism, include [[multiple sclerosis]], [[diabetes type I]], [[rheumatoid arthritis]] and [[Crohn's disease]]. As for multiple sclerosis, an article in the journal ''Nature'' dated May 2010 (Baranzini et al.: Genome, epigenome and RNA sequences of [[monozygotic twin]]s discordant for multiple sclerosis. Nature 2010, 464; S. 1351-1356 \u2013 for link see below) showed that this autoimmune disease is not caused by a genetic variation but the course and the treatability are considerably influenced by genetic dispositions. This research was based on analysing three monovular pairs of twins, of which one twin has contracted multiple sclerosis whereas the other one has not.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.efiweb.eu/ European Federation for Immunogenetics]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110210192027/http://www.ebi.ac.uk/imgt/ IMGT Databases at the European Bioinformatics Institute]\n* [http://www.womenshealth.gov/faq/autoimmune-diseases.cfm FAQ on autoimmune diseases by US Department for Health and Human Services]\n* [http://www.genome.gov/20019523 Homepage of the National Genome association studies]\n\n{{Genetics |expanded}}\n\n[[Category:Medical genetics]]\n[[Category:Branches of immunology]]\n", "name_user": "SaladH", "label": "safe", "comment": "citations", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Immunogenetics"}
{"title_page": "Nadine Gogolla", "text_new": "{{short description|American neuroscientist}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Nadine Gogolla\n| image             = \n| image_size        = \n| caption           = \n| birth_date        = \n| birth_place       = \n| nationality       = German\n| fields            = Neuroscience\n| workplaces        = Max Plank Institute of Neurobiology in Martinsried Germany\n| alma_mater        = B.S. University of Marburg, Germany, M.S. Inserm U546 Paris, France, PhD Friedrich Miescher Institute of Biomedical Research and University of Basel, Postdoctoral work at Harvard University\n| known_for         = Facial expression reflect emotional states in mice\n| awards            = Charles A. King Trust - Post-doctoral Research Fellowship Award, Human Frontiers Science Program (HFSP) Long-Term Fellowship, Jane Coffin Childs Memorial Fund for Medical Research, Ed Fisher Prize, Best Ph.D. Thesis Award, German National Academic Merit Foundation\n| Institutions      = Max Plank Institute\n}}\n'''Nadine Gogolla''' is a Research Group Leader at the [[Max Planck Institute of Neurobiology]] in [[Martinsried]], Germany as well as an Associate Faculty of the Graduate School for Systematic Neuroscience. Gogolla investigates the neural circuits underlying emotion to understand how the brain integrates external cues, feeling states, and emotions to make calculated behavioral decisions. Gogolla is known for her discovery using machine learning and [[Two-photon excitation microscopy|two-photon microscopy]] to classify mouse facial expressions into emotion-like categories and correlate these facial expressions with neural activity in the insular cortex.\n\n==Early Life and Education ==\nGogolla conducted her undergraduate studies in human biology at the [[University of Marburg]] in Germany.<ref name=\"neuro.mpg.de\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.neuro.mpg.de/2985279/cv|title=cv|website=www.neuro.mpg.de|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> Right after finishing her undergraduate degree in 2002, Gogolla completed her M.S. at [[Inserm]] U546 in Paris, France under the mentorship of Dr. [[Roland Liblau]] studying neuroimmune interactions in disease models.<ref name=\"neuro.mpg.de\"/> Later in 2002, Gogolla began her graduate studies in neurobiology at [[Friedrich Miescher Institute for Biomedical Research|Friedrich Miescher Institute]] of Biomedical Research affiliated with the [[University of Basel]] in Basel, [[Switzerland]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fmi.ch/|title=FMI - Friedrich Miescher Institute for Biomedical Research - Pico Caroni|last=|website=fmi.ch|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref name=\"neuro.mpg.de\"/> Under the mentorship of Dr. [[Pico Caroni]], Gogolla explored the regulatory mechanisms governing structural plasticity in the brain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fmi.ch/|title=FMI - Friedrich Miescher Institute for Biomedical Research - Pico Caroni|last=|website=fmi.ch|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nDuring her PhD, Gogolla published several first author papers in the journal Nature. In 2006, Gogolla published a paper in [[Nature Protocols]] outlining an innovative method to prepare organotypic hippocampal slice cultures for long-term live imaging up to 6 months in vitro.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gogolla|first=Nadine|last2=Galimberti|first2=Ivan|last3=DePaola|first3=Vincenzo|last4=Caroni|first4=Pico|date=August 2006|title=Preparation of organotypic hippocampal slice cultures for long-term live imaging|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/nprot.2006.168/|journal=Nature Protocols|language=en|volume=1|issue=3|pages=1165\u20131171|doi=10.1038/nprot.2006.168|issn=1750-2799}}</ref> Shortly after, Gogolla published another Nature Protocols paper outlining a novel method for long-term imaging of neural circuits in organotypic hippocampal slice cultures.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gogolla|first=Nadine|last2=Galimberti|first2=Ivan|last3=DePaola|first3=Vincenzo|last4=Caroni|first4=Pico|date=August 2006|title=Long-term live imaging of neuronal circuits in organotypic hippocampal slice cultures|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/nprot.2006.169|journal=Nature Protocols|language=en|volume=1|issue=3|pages=1223\u20131226|doi=10.1038/nprot.2006.169|issn=1750-2799}}</ref> Gogolla's third first author Nature Protocols paper was published in 2006 as well outlining a staining protocol for organotypic hippocampal slice cultures.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gogolla|first=Nadine|last2=Galimberti|first2=Ivan|last3=DePaola|first3=Vincenzo|last4=Caroni|first4=Pico|date=December 2006|title=Staining protocol for organotypic hippocampal slice cultures|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/nprot.2006.180|journal=Nature Protocols|language=en|volume=1|issue=5|pages=2452\u20132456|doi=10.1038/nprot.2006.180|issn=1750-2799}}</ref> Using these methods, Gogolla was able to graduate Summa Cum Laude the following year in 2007.<ref name=\"Gogolla 2007\">{{Cite thesis|title=Experience-dependent structural rearrangements of synaptic connectivity in the adult central nervous system|url=http://edoc.unibas.ch/diss/DissB_8177|publisher=University_of_Basel|date=2007|degree=Thesis|first=Nadine|last=Gogolla}}</ref> Gogolla's dissertation was titled \"Experience-dependent structural rearrangements of synaptic connectivity in the adult central nervous system\".<ref name=\"Gogolla 2007\"/> Her dissertation work highlighted the molecular mechanisms underlying experience dependent plasticity in the [[Mossy fiber (hippocampus)|mossy fiber]] pathway of the [[hippocampus]] and she explored how age and lifestyle effect these mechansims in vitro.<ref name=\"Gogolla 2007\"/> \n\nAfter completing her PhD in 2007, Gogolla began her postdoctoral training at [[Harvard University]] under the mentorship of Dr. [[Takao Hensch]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.neuro.mpg.de/2985279/cv|title=cv|website=www.neuro.mpg.de|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> While at Harvard, Gogolla explored the neurobiological mechanisms underlying critical periods of brain development.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://henschlab.mcb.harvard.edu/|title=Hensch Lab|website=Hensch Lab|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> During this time, Gogolla published a paper in Science showing that a part of the extracellular matrix, material known as [[Chondroitin sulfate proteoglycan|chondroitin sulfate proteglycan]]<nowiki/>s, build up in the [[amygdala]] forming [[Perineuronal net|perineuronal]] nets which protect fear memories from erasure.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gogolla|first=Nadine|last2=Caroni|first2=Pico|last3=L\u00fcthi|first3=Andreas|last4=Herry|first4=Cyril|date=2009-09-04|title=Perineuronal Nets Protect Fear Memories from Erasure|url=https://science.sciencemag.org/content/325/5945/1258|journal=Science|language=en|volume=325|issue=5945|pages=1258\u20131261|doi=10.1126/science.1174146|issn=0036-8075|pmid=19729657}}</ref> Intriguingly, degrading these [[Perineuronal net|perineuronal nets]] in adulthood using an enzyme that degrades chondroitin sulfate proteglycans, rendered fear memories susceptible to extinction again.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gogolla|first=Nadine|last2=Caroni|first2=Pico|last3=L\u00fcthi|first3=Andreas|last4=Herry|first4=Cyril|date=2009-09-04|title=Perineuronal Nets Protect Fear Memories from Erasure|url=https://science.sciencemag.org/content/325/5945/1258|journal=Science|language=en|volume=325|issue=5945|pages=1258\u20131261|doi=10.1126/science.1174146|issn=0036-8075|pmid=19729657}}</ref> This finding could inspire translational research towards treatments for disorders such as [[Posttraumatic stress disorder|post-traumatic stress disorder]], characterized by an inability to eliminate fear-inducing memories leading to behavioral disruptions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/news-blog/can-fearful-memories-be-erased-2009-09-03/|title=Can fearful memories be erased?|last=Peeples|first=Lynne|website=Scientific American Blog Network|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> In 2009, Gogolla published a first author paper in the Journal of Neurodevelopmental Disorders.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gogolla|first=Nadine|last2=Leblanc|first2=Jocelyn|last3=Quast|first3=Kathleen|last4=S\u00fcdhof|first4=Thomas|last5=Fagiolini|first5=Michela|last6=Hensch|first6=Takao|date=2009-06-01|title=Common circuit defect of excitatory-inhibitory balance in mouse models of autism|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/45389745_Common_circuit_defect_of_excitatory-inhibitory_balance_in_mouse_models_of_autism|journal=Journal of neurodevelopmental disorders|volume=1|pages=172\u201381|doi=10.1007/s11689-009-9023-x}}</ref> Her study explored the idea that the complexity of [[Autism spectrum|Autism Spectrum Disorders]] (ASD) is a result of aberrant excitatory/inhibitory neural circuit regulation during critical periods in development.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gogolla|first=Nadine|last2=Leblanc|first2=Jocelyn|last3=Quast|first3=Kathleen|last4=S\u00fcdhof|first4=Thomas|last5=Fagiolini|first5=Michela|last6=Hensch|first6=Takao|date=2009-06-01|title=Common circuit defect of excitatory-inhibitory balance in mouse models of autism|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/45389745_Common_circuit_defect_of_excitatory-inhibitory_balance_in_mouse_models_of_autism|journal=Journal of neurodevelopmental disorders|volume=1|pages=172\u201381|doi=10.1007/s11689-009-9023-x}}</ref> Gogolla narrowed in on [[Parvalbumin]] (PV) positive inhibitory [[Interneuron|interneurons]] since they mediate experience-dependent neural circuit refinement in development, and she explored the expression of these neurons across multiple ASD mouse models.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gogolla|first=Nadine|last2=Leblanc|first2=Jocelyn|last3=Quast|first3=Kathleen|last4=S\u00fcdhof|first4=Thomas|last5=Fagiolini|first5=Michela|last6=Hensch|first6=Takao|date=2009-06-01|title=Common circuit defect of excitatory-inhibitory balance in mouse models of autism|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/45389745_Common_circuit_defect_of_excitatory-inhibitory_balance_in_mouse_models_of_autism|journal=Journal of neurodevelopmental disorders|volume=1|pages=172\u201381|doi=10.1007/s11689-009-9023-x}}</ref> Gogolla strikingly found a PV positive neuron deficit in the neocortex across multiple ASD mouse models highlighting a critical role for these neurons in normal development and the potential of this circuit defect as a target for ASD prevention.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gogolla|first=Nadine|last2=Leblanc|first2=Jocelyn|last3=Quast|first3=Kathleen|last4=S\u00fcdhof|first4=Thomas|last5=Fagiolini|first5=Michela|last6=Hensch|first6=Takao|date=2009-06-01|title=Common circuit defect of excitatory-inhibitory balance in mouse models of autism|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/45389745_Common_circuit_defect_of_excitatory-inhibitory_balance_in_mouse_models_of_autism|journal=Journal of neurodevelopmental disorders|volume=1|pages=172\u201381|doi=10.1007/s11689-009-9023-x}}</ref>  Gogolla then began to explore the [[insular cortex]] (IC), a brain region that is a part of the cerebral cortex, that seems to play a role in many complex brain processes including multisensory integration, representation of emotions, motor control, and complex social processes such as empathy.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gogolla|first=Nadine|date=2017-06-19|title=The insular cortex|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0960982217305468|journal=Current Biology|language=en|volume=27|issue=12|pages=R580\u2013R586|doi=10.1016/j.cub.2017.05.010|issn=0960-9822}}</ref> Integration of sensory, emotional, and cognitive information allows for these diverse functions of the IC, so Gogolla sought to understand how this integration occurs and how it is aberrantly functioning in ASD models, both idiopathic and [[Genetic disorder|monogenic]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gogolla|first=Nadine|last2=Takesian|first2=Anne\u00a0E.|last3=Feng|first3=Guoping|last4=Fagiolini|first4=Michela|last5=Hensch|first5=Takao\u00a0K.|date=2014-08-20|title=Sensory Integration in Mouse Insular Cortex Reflects GABA Circuit Maturation|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0896627314005790|journal=Neuron|language=en|volume=83|issue=4|pages=894\u2013905|doi=10.1016/j.neuron.2014.06.033|issn=0896-6273}}</ref> Through in vivo fluorescence imaging techniques, Gogolla was able to record from the IC and observe multisensory integration emerging in the IC throughout early development, but this process did not occur in ASD models.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gogolla|first=Nadine|last2=Takesian|first2=Anne\u00a0E.|last3=Feng|first3=Guoping|last4=Fagiolini|first4=Michela|last5=Hensch|first5=Takao\u00a0K.|date=2014-08-20|title=Sensory Integration in Mouse Insular Cortex Reflects GABA Circuit Maturation|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0896627314005790|journal=Neuron|language=en|volume=83|issue=4|pages=894\u2013905|doi=10.1016/j.neuron.2014.06.033|issn=0896-6273}}</ref> She further found that expression of inhibitory neuron markers was decreased compared to controls in the IC of ASD mouse models suggesting that inhibitory/excitatory circuit balance is disrupted.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gogolla|first=Nadine|last2=Takesian|first2=Anne\u00a0E.|last3=Feng|first3=Guoping|last4=Fagiolini|first4=Michela|last5=Hensch|first5=Takao\u00a0K.|date=2014-08-20|title=Sensory Integration in Mouse Insular Cortex Reflects GABA Circuit Maturation|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0896627314005790|journal=Neuron|language=en|volume=83|issue=4|pages=894\u2013905|doi=10.1016/j.neuron.2014.06.033|issn=0896-6273}}</ref> Following this result, they pharmacologically enhanced inhibitory signalling in juvenile mice via systemic injections of [[diazepam]] for two weeks and found that it rescued integration deficits in ASD models.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gogolla|first=Nadine|last2=Takesian|first2=Anne\u00a0E.|last3=Feng|first3=Guoping|last4=Fagiolini|first4=Michela|last5=Hensch|first5=Takao\u00a0K.|date=2014-08-20|title=Sensory Integration in Mouse Insular Cortex Reflects GABA Circuit Maturation|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0896627314005790|journal=Neuron|language=en|volume=83|issue=4|pages=894\u2013905|doi=10.1016/j.neuron.2014.06.033|issn=0896-6273}}</ref> Intriguingly, enhancing inhibitory transmission pharmacologically in adult mice had no effect on neural circuit balance nor multisensory integration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.conte.harvard.edu/news/2014/8/1/rescuing-sensory-integration-in-mouse-models-of-autism|title=Rescuing sensory integration in mouse models of autism|website=Conte Center at Harvard|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> Their finding suggests that enhancing inhibitory transmission during a critical developmental period can restore inhibitory/excitatory balance and restore normal multisensory integration functions of the IC.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gogolla|first=Nadine|last2=Takesian|first2=Anne\u00a0E.|last3=Feng|first3=Guoping|last4=Fagiolini|first4=Michela|last5=Hensch|first5=Takao\u00a0K.|date=2014-08-20|title=Sensory Integration in Mouse Insular Cortex Reflects GABA Circuit Maturation|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0896627314005790|journal=Neuron|language=en|volume=83|issue=4|pages=894\u2013905|doi=10.1016/j.neuron.2014.06.033|issn=0896-6273}}</ref> Gogolla's research, published in Neuron in 2014, received a large amount of attention due to the new insights in provided in how ASD might manifest in the human brain and lead to ASD type behaviors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.harvard.edu/gazette/story/2014/07/help-for-halting-autism-symptoms/|title=Help for halting autism symptoms|date=2014-07-31|website=Harvard Gazette|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n== Career and Research  ==\nAfter finishing her posdoctoral work at Harvard, Gogolla moved back to Germany in 2013 where she started a faculty position at the [[Max Planck Institute of Neurobiology|Max Plank Institute of Neurobiology]] in Martinsried, Germany.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.harvard.edu/gazette/story/2014/07/help-for-halting-autism-symptoms/|title=Help for halting autism symptoms|date=2014-07-31|website=Harvard Gazette|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> Gogolla is also an Associate Faculty in the Graduate School of Systemic Neurosciences at the Munich Center for Neurosciences in the [[Ludwig Maximilian University of Munich|Ludwig-Maximilians-Universitat Munchen]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gsn.uni-muenchen.de/people/faculty/associate/gogolla/index.html|title=Dr. Nadine Gogolla|last=|first=|date=|website=Graduate School of Systemic Neuroscience - Munich Center for Neuroscience Brain and Mind|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> Gogolla currently leads a group of scientists at MPI where her research program focuses on exploring the neural circuits of the insular cortex as well as their connections to the prefrontal cortex and other limbic structures as a means to understand how it plays a part in so many diverse brain processes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.neuro.mpg.de/gogolla|title=Circuits for Emotion|website=www.neuro.mpg.de|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> A better understanding of the neural circuit mechanisms mediating diverse functions of the insular cortex, such as emotional regulation, empathy, and social behavior, will give insight into how processes are altered in disease states such as schizophrenia, ASD, addiction, and mood disorders.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.neuro.mpg.de/gogolla|title=Circuits for Emotion|website=www.neuro.mpg.de|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> To probe insular neural circuits, Gogolla and her lab use in vivo two-photon calcium imaging to record neural activity while mice are processing emotionally relevant stimuli, and they further use innovative behavioral assays, optogenetic techniques, and [[machine learning]] algorithms to link neural activity to behavior, manipulate neural circuits, and decode the activity of behaviorally and emotionally relevant IC neural ensembles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.neuro.mpg.de/gogolla|title=Circuits for Emotion|website=www.neuro.mpg.de|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> \n\nIn 2017, Gogolla wrote a review on the IC describing its anatomical location and connectivity, its role as an integration hub, its role in sensory processing, homeostatic regulation, emotional regulation, and valence processing as well as its role in driving behavior.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gogolla|first=Nadine|date=2017-06-19|title=The insular cortex|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0960982217305468|journal=Current Biology|language=en|volume=27|issue=12|pages=R580\u2013R586|doi=10.1016/j.cub.2017.05.010|issn=0960-9822}}</ref>  Gogolla also explored the human IC and how it is affected in different neurological and psychiatric disorders to emphasize the importance of gaining a better understanding of this region, an integral goal of her research program.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gogolla|first=Nadine|date=2017-06-19|title=The insular cortex|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0960982217305468|journal=Current Biology|language=en|volume=27|issue=12|pages=R580\u2013R586|doi=10.1016/j.cub.2017.05.010|issn=0960-9822}}</ref> \n\nIn 2019, Gogolla described role of the posterior insular cortex (pIC) to central amygdala projection in the mediating anxiety-related behaviors as well as the posterior insular cortex to nucleus accumbens projection in the inhibition of feeding behaviors.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gehrlach|first=Daniel A.|last2=Dolensek|first2=Nejc|last3=Klein|first3=Alexandra S.|last4=Roy Chowdhury|first4=Ritu|last5=Matthys|first5=Arthur|last6=Jungh\u00e4nel|first6=Michaela|last7=Gaitanos|first7=Thomas N.|last8=Podgornik|first8=Alja|last9=Black|first9=Thomas D.|last10=Reddy Vaka|first10=Narasimha|last11=Conzelmann|first11=Karl-Klaus|date=September 2019|title=Aversive state processing in the posterior insular cortex|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/s41593-019-0469-1|journal=Nature Neuroscience|language=en|volume=22|issue=9|pages=1424\u20131437|doi=10.1038/s41593-019-0469-1|issn=1546-1726}}</ref> Using [[optogenetics]], they found that stimulating the pIC caused aversive behaviors as well as increased autonomic responses.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gehrlach|first=Daniel A.|last2=Dolensek|first2=Nejc|last3=Klein|first3=Alexandra S.|last4=Roy Chowdhury|first4=Ritu|last5=Matthys|first5=Arthur|last6=Jungh\u00e4nel|first6=Michaela|last7=Gaitanos|first7=Thomas N.|last8=Podgornik|first8=Alja|last9=Black|first9=Thomas D.|last10=Reddy Vaka|first10=Narasimha|last11=Conzelmann|first11=Karl-Klaus|date=September 2019|title=Aversive state processing in the posterior insular cortex|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/s41593-019-0469-1|journal=Nature Neuroscience|language=en|volume=22|issue=9|pages=1424\u20131437|doi=10.1038/s41593-019-0469-1|issn=1546-1726}}</ref> Then, using in vivo [[Two-photon excitation microscopy|two-photon calcium imaging]], Gogolla and her team were able to record calcium transients in neurons in the pIC as an indicator of neural activity to establish a causal relationship between pIC activity and the convergence and integration of acute sensory stimuli as well as sustained affective and homeostatic states.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gehrlach|first=Daniel A.|last2=Dolensek|first2=Nejc|last3=Klein|first3=Alexandra S.|last4=Roy Chowdhury|first4=Ritu|last5=Matthys|first5=Arthur|last6=Jungh\u00e4nel|first6=Michaela|last7=Gaitanos|first7=Thomas N.|last8=Podgornik|first8=Alja|last9=Black|first9=Thomas D.|last10=Reddy Vaka|first10=Narasimha|last11=Conzelmann|first11=Karl-Klaus|date=September 2019|title=Aversive state processing in the posterior insular cortex|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/s41593-019-0469-1|journal=Nature Neuroscience|language=en|volume=22|issue=9|pages=1424\u20131437|doi=10.1038/s41593-019-0469-1|issn=1546-1726}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, Gogolla and her team published a groundbreaking paper using innovative machine learning and two-photon technologies to show that mouse facial expressions correlate with internal emotional states and that neural activity in the IC is closely correlated with specific facial expressions in mice.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dolensek|first=Nejc|last2=Gehrlach|first2=Daniel A.|last3=Klein|first3=Alexandra S.|last4=Gogolla|first4=Nadine|date=2020-04-03|title=Facial expressions of emotion states and their neuronal correlates in mice|url=https://science.sciencemag.org/content/368/6486/89|journal=Science|language=en|volume=368|issue=6486|pages=89\u201394|doi=10.1126/science.aaz9468|issn=0036-8075|pmid=32241948}}</ref> Gogolla was inspired by a 2014 Cell paper stating that emotions represent brain states and should last for a discrete amount of time after the stimulus that evoked them and, importantly, they should scale to the  strength of the stimulus that evoked them.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Abbott|first=Alison|date=2020-04-02|title=Artificial intelligence decodes the facial expressions of mice|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-020-01002-7|journal=Nature|language=en|doi=10.1038/d41586-020-01002-7}}</ref> As such, Gogolla presented salient stimuli to headfixed mice, such as sweet and bitter tastes or slightly painful shocks, meant to trigger specific emotional responses.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Abbott|first=Alison|date=2020-04-02|title=Artificial intelligence decodes the facial expressions of mice|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-020-01002-7|journal=Nature|language=en|doi=10.1038/d41586-020-01002-7}}</ref> While they presented these stimuli, they recorded the faces of the mice and then broke down the video recordings into facial-muscle movements that they then used to train a machine learning algorithm to detect distinct facial-muscle movements that correlate with emotions.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Abbott|first=Alison|date=2020-04-02|title=Artificial intelligence decodes the facial expressions of mice|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-020-01002-7|journal=Nature|language=en|doi=10.1038/d41586-020-01002-7}}</ref> For example, they found that when a mouse experiences pain, its nose drooped and its ears tilted downward.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/02/world/mice-facial-expressions-scn-trnd/index.html|title=Mice make different faces depending on how they feel -- and that could impact how we treat mood disorders, a new study says|first=Scottie |last=Andrew|website=CNN|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> Not only was the algorithm able to detect distinct facial expressions that correlated to the distinct emotion-evoking stimuli, but the facial expressions were also graded based on the intensity of the stimulus presented.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Abbott|first=Alison|date=2020-04-02|title=Artificial intelligence decodes the facial expressions of mice|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-020-01002-7|journal=Nature|language=en|doi=10.1038/d41586-020-01002-7}}</ref> This unbiased and quantitative approach to recognizing facial expressions, and thus emotional state readouts, will finally allow neuroscientists to ask and answer questions about how the brain processes emotion and drives motivated behaviors.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dolensek|first=Nejc|last2=Gehrlach|first2=Daniel A.|last3=Klein|first3=Alexandra S.|last4=Gogolla|first4=Nadine|date=2020-04-03|title=Facial expressions of emotion states and their neuronal correlates in mice|url=https://science.sciencemag.org/content/368/6486/89|journal=Science|language=en|volume=368|issue=6486|pages=89\u201394|doi=10.1126/science.aaz9468|issn=0036-8075|pmid=32241948}}</ref> The second part of the study focused on the neural basis of these facial expressions, or emotional states. Gogolla's team recorded neurons in the IC using two-photon imaging such that they could observe neurons with single-cell resolution to observe neurons that only fire when particular facial expressions are performed.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Abbott|first=Alison|date=2020-04-02|title=Artificial intelligence decodes the facial expressions of mice|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-020-01002-7|journal=Nature|language=en|doi=10.1038/d41586-020-01002-7}}</ref> Further, they used [[optogenetics]] to drive specific neural circuits known to be involved in specific emotional states and trigger the corresponding facial expressions in mice.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Abbott|first=Alison|date=2020-04-02|title=Artificial intelligence decodes the facial expressions of mice|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-020-01002-7|journal=Nature|language=en|doi=10.1038/d41586-020-01002-7}}</ref> This study emphasizes the power of applying machine learning techniques to neuroscience questions since the faces of animals may have appeared to be emotionless to human observers but machine learning algorithms were able to detect the subtle changes that indicate distinct emotional states.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2020/04/200402144430.htm|title=The facial expressions of mice: The face of a mouse reveals its emotions|website=ScienceDaily|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> These findings have dramatically improved our ability to dissect how and where emotions arise in the brain, now that we can detect and quantify them in animal models, which opens up the potential to translate these findings to the human brain to understand brain disorders characterized by aberrations in emotional processing and emotional regulation such as mood disorders.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/02/world/mice-facial-expressions-scn-trnd/index.html|title=Mice make different faces depending on how they feel -- and that could impact how we treat mood disorders, a new study says|first=Scottie |last=Andrew|website=CNN|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and Honors ==\n\n* '''2017''': ERC Starting Grant \"Insular Anxiety\"<ref name=\"neuro.mpg.de\"/>\n* '''2011 \u2013 2013:''' Charles A. King Trust, Post-doctoral Research Fellowship Award<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hria.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/King_Basic_Grant_Recipients_2003-2019.pdf|title=Charles A. King Trust Postdoctoral Fellowship Program Basic Science|last=|first=|date=|website=King Basic Grant Recipients|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 5, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.conte.harvard.edu/news/2014/8/1/rescuing-sensory-integration-in-mouse-models-of-autism|title=Rescuing sensory integration in mouse models of autism|website=Conte Center at Harvard|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n* '''2008 \u2013 2011:''' Human Frontiers Science Program (HFSP) Long-Term Fellowship<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hfsp.org/awardees/awards?field_countries_target_id&field_nationalities_target_id&field_award_type_target_id=All&page=115|title=Awards {{!}} Human Frontier Science Program|website=www.hfsp.org|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n* '''2008 \u2013 2011:''' Jane Coffin Childs Memorial Fund for Medical Research \u2013 Long-Term Fellowship (declined in favor of HFSP Award)<ref name=\"neuro.mpg.de\"/>\n* '''2008:''' Ed Fisher Prize, Best Ph.D. Thesis Award, Friedrich Miescher Institute, Basel<ref name=\"neuro.mpg.de\"/>\n* '''1997 - 2002''': German National Academic Merit Foundation (Studienstiftung des Deutschen Volkes), full scholarship<ref name=\"neuro.mpg.de\"/>\n\n==Selected publications==\n*Dolensek, N., Gehrlach, D. A., Klein, A. S. & '''Gogolla''', N. ''Science'' <nowiki>https://www.doi.org/10.1126/science.aaz9468</nowiki> (2020).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dolensek|first=Nejc|last2=Gehrlach|first2=Daniel A.|last3=Klein|first3=Alexandra S.|last4=Gogolla|first4=Nadine|date=2020-04-03|title=Facial expressions of emotion states and their neuronal correlates in mice|url=https://science.sciencemag.org/content/368/6486/89|journal=Science|language=en|volume=368|issue=6486|pages=89\u201394|doi=10.1126/science.aaz9468|issn=0036-8075|pmid=32241948}}</ref>\n*{{Cite journal|\nlast=Gehrlach|first=D.A.|\nlast2=Dolensek|first2=N.|\nlast3=Klein|first3=A.S.|\nlast4=Roy Chowdhury|first4=R.|\nlast5=Matthys|first5=A.|\nlast6=Jungh\u00e4nel|first6=M.|\nlast7=Gaitanos|first7=T.N.|\nlast8=Podgornik|first8=A.|\nlast9=Black|first9=T.D.|\nlast10=Reddy Vaka|first10=N.|\nlast11=Conzelmann|first11=K.-K.|\nlast12='''Gogolla'''|first12=N.|\ndate=2019-08-27|\ntitle=Aversive state processing in the posterior insular cortex|\njournal=Nature Neuroscience|\nvolume=22|\nissue=9|\npages=1424\u20131437|\ndoi=10.1038/s41593-019-0469-1|\npmid=31455886}}\n*'''Gogolla N''' (2017). The insular cortex. Curr Biol 27: R580-R586 (2017).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gogolla|first=Nadine|date=2017-06-19|title=The insular cortex|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0960982217305468|journal=Current Biology|language=en|volume=27|issue=12|pages=R580\u2013R586|doi=10.1016/j.cub.2017.05.010|issn=0960-9822}}</ref>\n*{{Cite journal|\nlast='''Gogolla'''|first=N.|\nlast2=Takesian|first2=A.E.|\nlast3=Feng|first3=G.|\nlast4=Fagiolini|first4=M.|\nlast5=Hensch|first5=T.K.|\ndate=2014-08-20|\ntitle=Sensory Integration in Mouse Insular Cortex Reflects GABA Circuit Maturation|\njournal=Neuron|\nvolume=83|\nissue=4|\npages=894\u2013905|\ndoi=10.1016/j.neuron.2014.06.033|\npmid=25088363}}\n*{{Cite journal|\nlast='''Gogolla'''|first=N.|\nlast2=Caroni|first2=P.|\nlast3=Luthi|first3=A.|\nlast4=Herry|first4=C.|\ndate=2009-09-04|\ntitle=Perineuronal nets protect fear memories from erasure|\njournal=Science|\nvolume=325|\nissue=5945|\npages=1258\u20131261|\ndoi=10.1126/science.1174146|\npmid=19729657}}\n*{{Cite journal|\nlast='''Gogolla'''|first=N.|\nlast2=LeBlanc|first2=J.J.|\nlast3=Quast|first3=K.B.|\nlast4=S\u00fcdhof|first4=T.C.|\nlast5=Fagiolini|first5=M.|\nlast6=Hensch|first6=T.K.|\ndate=2009-06-04|\ntitle=Perineuronal nets protect fear memories from erasure|\njournal=Journal of Neurodevelopmental Disorders|\nvolume=1|\nissue=2|\npages=172\u2013181|\ndoi=10.1007/s11689-009-9023-x|\npmid=20664807}}\n*'''Gogolla N'''*, LeBlanc JJ*, Quast KB*, S\u00fcdhof TC, Fagiolini M, Hensch TK (2009). Common circuit defect of excitatory-inhibitory balance in mouse models of autism. J Neurodev Disorders 1: 172-181.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gogolla|first=Nadine|last2=Leblanc|first2=Jocelyn J.|last3=Quast|first3=Kathleen B.|last4=S\u00fcdhof|first4=Thomas C.|last5=Fagiolini|first5=Michela|last6=Hensch|first6=Takao K.|date=June 2009|title=Common circuit defect of excitatory-inhibitory balance in mouse models of autism|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20664807|journal=Journal of Neurodevelopmental Disorders|volume=1|issue=2|pages=172\u2013181|doi=10.1007/s11689-009-9023-x|issn=1866-1955|pmc=2906812|pmid=20664807}}</ref>\n*'''Gogolla N''', Galimberti I, Deguchi Y, Caroni P (2009). Wnt signaling mediates experience-related regulation of synapse numbers and mossy fiber connectivities in the adult hippocampus. Neuron 62: 510-525.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.neuro.mpg.de/2985509/publications|title=Publications|website=www.neuro.mpg.de|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n* Galimberti I*, '''Gogolla N'''*, Alberi S, Santos AF, Muller D, Caroni P (2006). Long-term rearrangements of hippocampal mossy fiber terminal connectivity in the adult regulated by experience. Neuron 50: 749-763.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.neuro.mpg.de/2985509/publications|title=Publications|website=www.neuro.mpg.de|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n* '''Gogolla N'''*, Galimberti I*, De Paola V, Caroni P (2006). Preparation of organotypic hippocampal slice\u00a0 cultures for long-term live imaging. Nature Protocols 1: 1165-1171.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.neuro.mpg.de/2985509/publications|title=Publications|website=www.neuro.mpg.de|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n* '''Gogolla N'''*, Galimberti I*, De Paola V, Caroni P (2006). Long-term live imaging of neuronal circuits in organotypic slice cultures. Nature Protocols 1: 1223\u20131226.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.neuro.mpg.de/2985509/publications|title=Publications|website=www.neuro.mpg.de|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n* '''Gogolla N'''*, Galimberti I*, De Paola V, Caroni P (2006). Staining protocol for organotypic hippocampal slice cultures. Nature Protocols 1: 2452\u20132456.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.neuro.mpg.de/2985509/publications|title=Publications|website=www.neuro.mpg.de|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{google scholar id|r5uNjooAAAAJ}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gogolla, Nadine}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American women scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:Max Planck Society faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Basel alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American neuroscientist}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Nadine Gogolla\n| image             = \n| image_size        = \n| caption           = \n| birth_date        = \n| birth_place       = \n| nationality       = German\n| fields            = Neuroscience\n| workplaces        = Max Plank Institute of Neurobiology in Martinsried Germany\n| alma_mater        = B.S. University of Marburg, Germany, M.S. Inserm U546 Paris, France, PhD Friedrich Miescher Institute of Biomedical Research and University of Basel, Postdoctoral work at Harvard University\n| known_for         = Facial expression reflect emotional states in mice\n| awards            = Charles A. King Trust - Post-doctoral Research Fellowship Award, Human Frontiers Science Program (HFSP) Long-Term Fellowship, Jane Coffin Childs Memorial Fund for Medical Research, Ed Fisher Prize, Best Ph.D. Thesis Award, German National Academic Merit Foundation\n| Institutions      = Max Plank Institute\n}}\n'''Nadine Gogolla''' is a Research Group Leader at the [[Max Planck Institute of Neurobiology]] in [[Martinsried]], Germany as well as an Associate Faculty of the Graduate School for Systematic Neuroscience. Gogolla investigates the neural circuits underlying emotion to understand how the brain integrates external cues, feeling states, and emotions to make calculated behavioral decisions. Gogolla is known for her discovery using machine learning and [[Two-photon excitation microscopy|two-photon microscopy]] to classify mouse facial expressions into emotion-like categories and correlate these facial expressions with neural activity in the insular cortex.\n\n==Early Life and Education ==\nGogolla conducted her undergraduate studies in human biology at the [[University of Marburg]] in Germany.<ref name=\"neuro.mpg.de\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.neuro.mpg.de/2985279/cv|title=cv|website=www.neuro.mpg.de|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> Right after finishing her undergraduate degree in 2002, Gogolla completed her M.S. at [[Inserm]] U546 in Paris, France under the mentorship of Dr. [[Roland Liblau]] studying neuroimmune interactions in disease models.<ref name=\"neuro.mpg.de\"/> Later in 2002, Gogolla began her graduate studies in neurobiology at [[Friedrich Miescher Institute for Biomedical Research|Friedrich Miescher Institute]] of Biomedical Research affiliated with the [[University of Basel]] in Basel, [[Switzerland]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fmi.ch/|title=FMI - Friedrich Miescher Institute for Biomedical Research - Pico Caroni|last=|website=fmi.ch|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref name=\"neuro.mpg.de\"/> Under the mentorship of Dr. [[Pico Caroni]], Gogolla explored the regulatory mechanisms governing structural plasticity in the brain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fmi.ch/|title=FMI - Friedrich Miescher Institute for Biomedical Research - Pico Caroni|last=|website=fmi.ch|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nDuring her PhD, Gogolla published several first author papers in the journal Nature. In 2006, Gogolla published a paper in [[Nature Protocols]] outlining an innovative method to prepare organotypic hippocampal slice cultures for long-term live imaging up to 6 months in vitro.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gogolla|first=Nadine|last2=Galimberti|first2=Ivan|last3=DePaola|first3=Vincenzo|last4=Caroni|first4=Pico|date=August 2006|title=Preparation of organotypic hippocampal slice cultures for long-term live imaging|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/nprot.2006.168/|journal=Nature Protocols|language=en|volume=1|issue=3|pages=1165\u20131171|doi=10.1038/nprot.2006.168|issn=1750-2799}}</ref> Shortly after, Gogolla published another Nature Protocols paper outlining a novel method for long-term imaging of neural circuits in organotypic hippocampal slice cultures.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gogolla|first=Nadine|last2=Galimberti|first2=Ivan|last3=DePaola|first3=Vincenzo|last4=Caroni|first4=Pico|date=August 2006|title=Long-term live imaging of neuronal circuits in organotypic hippocampal slice cultures|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/nprot.2006.169|journal=Nature Protocols|language=en|volume=1|issue=3|pages=1223\u20131226|doi=10.1038/nprot.2006.169|issn=1750-2799}}</ref> Gogolla's third first author Nature Protocols paper was published in 2006 as well outlining a staining protocol for organotypic hippocampal slice cultures.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gogolla|first=Nadine|last2=Galimberti|first2=Ivan|last3=DePaola|first3=Vincenzo|last4=Caroni|first4=Pico|date=December 2006|title=Staining protocol for organotypic hippocampal slice cultures|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/nprot.2006.180|journal=Nature Protocols|language=en|volume=1|issue=5|pages=2452\u20132456|doi=10.1038/nprot.2006.180|issn=1750-2799}}</ref> Using these methods, Gogolla was able to graduate Summa Cum Laude the following year in 2007.<ref name=\"Gogolla 2007\">{{Cite thesis|title=Experience-dependent structural rearrangements of synaptic connectivity in the adult central nervous system|url=http://edoc.unibas.ch/diss/DissB_8177|publisher=University_of_Basel|date=2007|degree=Thesis|first=Nadine|last=Gogolla}}</ref> Gogolla's dissertation was titled \"Experience-dependent structural rearrangements of synaptic connectivity in the adult central nervous system\".<ref name=\"Gogolla 2007\"/> Her dissertation work highlighted the molecular mechanisms underlying experience dependent plasticity in the [[Mossy fiber (hippocampus)|mossy fiber]] pathway of the [[hippocampus]] and she explored how age and lifestyle effect these mechansims in vitro.<ref name=\"Gogolla 2007\"/> \n\nAfter completing her PhD in 2007, Gogolla began her postdoctoral training at [[Harvard University]] under the mentorship of Dr. [[Takao Hensch]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.neuro.mpg.de/2985279/cv|title=cv|website=www.neuro.mpg.de|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> While at Harvard, Gogolla explored the neurobiological mechanisms underlying critical periods of brain development.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://henschlab.mcb.harvard.edu/|title=Hensch Lab|website=Hensch Lab|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> During this time, Gogolla published a paper in Science showing that a part of the extracellular matrix, material known as [[Chondroitin sulfate proteoglycan|chondroitin sulfate proteglycan]]<nowiki/>s, build up in the [[amygdala]] forming [[Perineuronal net|perineuronal]] nets which protect fear memories from erasure.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gogolla|first=Nadine|last2=Caroni|first2=Pico|last3=L\u00fcthi|first3=Andreas|last4=Herry|first4=Cyril|date=2009-09-04|title=Perineuronal Nets Protect Fear Memories from Erasure|url=https://science.sciencemag.org/content/325/5945/1258|journal=Science|language=en|volume=325|issue=5945|pages=1258\u20131261|doi=10.1126/science.1174146|issn=0036-8075|pmid=19729657}}</ref> Intriguingly, degrading these [[Perineuronal net|perineuronal nets]] in adulthood using an enzyme that degrades chondroitin sulfate proteglycans, rendered fear memories susceptible to extinction again.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gogolla|first=Nadine|last2=Caroni|first2=Pico|last3=L\u00fcthi|first3=Andreas|last4=Herry|first4=Cyril|date=2009-09-04|title=Perineuronal Nets Protect Fear Memories from Erasure|url=https://science.sciencemag.org/content/325/5945/1258|journal=Science|language=en|volume=325|issue=5945|pages=1258\u20131261|doi=10.1126/science.1174146|issn=0036-8075|pmid=19729657}}</ref> This finding could inspire translational research towards treatments for disorders such as [[Posttraumatic stress disorder|post-traumatic stress disorder]], characterized by an inability to eliminate fear-inducing memories leading to behavioral disruptions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/news-blog/can-fearful-memories-be-erased-2009-09-03/|title=Can fearful memories be erased?|last=Peeples|first=Lynne|website=Scientific American Blog Network|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> In 2009, Gogolla published a first author paper in the Journal of Neurodevelopmental Disorders.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gogolla|first=Nadine|last2=Leblanc|first2=Jocelyn|last3=Quast|first3=Kathleen|last4=S\u00fcdhof|first4=Thomas|last5=Fagiolini|first5=Michela|last6=Hensch|first6=Takao|date=2009-06-01|title=Common circuit defect of excitatory-inhibitory balance in mouse models of autism|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/45389745_Common_circuit_defect_of_excitatory-inhibitory_balance_in_mouse_models_of_autism|journal=Journal of neurodevelopmental disorders|volume=1|pages=172\u201381|doi=10.1007/s11689-009-9023-x}}</ref> Her study explored the idea that the complexity of [[Autism spectrum|Autism Spectrum Disorders]] (ASD) is a result of aberrant excitatory/inhibitory neural circuit regulation during critical periods in development.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gogolla|first=Nadine|last2=Leblanc|first2=Jocelyn|last3=Quast|first3=Kathleen|last4=S\u00fcdhof|first4=Thomas|last5=Fagiolini|first5=Michela|last6=Hensch|first6=Takao|date=2009-06-01|title=Common circuit defect of excitatory-inhibitory balance in mouse models of autism|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/45389745_Common_circuit_defect_of_excitatory-inhibitory_balance_in_mouse_models_of_autism|journal=Journal of neurodevelopmental disorders|volume=1|pages=172\u201381|doi=10.1007/s11689-009-9023-x}}</ref> Gogolla narrowed in on [[Parvalbumin]] (PV) positive inhibitory [[Interneuron|interneurons]] since they mediate experience-dependent neural circuit refinement in development, and she explored the expression of these neurons across multiple ASD mouse models.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gogolla|first=Nadine|last2=Leblanc|first2=Jocelyn|last3=Quast|first3=Kathleen|last4=S\u00fcdhof|first4=Thomas|last5=Fagiolini|first5=Michela|last6=Hensch|first6=Takao|date=2009-06-01|title=Common circuit defect of excitatory-inhibitory balance in mouse models of autism|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/45389745_Common_circuit_defect_of_excitatory-inhibitory_balance_in_mouse_models_of_autism|journal=Journal of neurodevelopmental disorders|volume=1|pages=172\u201381|doi=10.1007/s11689-009-9023-x}}</ref> Gogolla strikingly found a PV positive neuron deficit in the neocortex across multiple ASD mouse models highlighting a critical role for these neurons in normal development and the potential of this circuit defect as a target for ASD prevention.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gogolla|first=Nadine|last2=Leblanc|first2=Jocelyn|last3=Quast|first3=Kathleen|last4=S\u00fcdhof|first4=Thomas|last5=Fagiolini|first5=Michela|last6=Hensch|first6=Takao|date=2009-06-01|title=Common circuit defect of excitatory-inhibitory balance in mouse models of autism|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/45389745_Common_circuit_defect_of_excitatory-inhibitory_balance_in_mouse_models_of_autism|journal=Journal of neurodevelopmental disorders|volume=1|pages=172\u201381|doi=10.1007/s11689-009-9023-x}}</ref>  Gogolla then began to explore the [[insular cortex]] (IC), a brain region that is a part of the cerebral cortex, that seems to play a role in many complex brain processes including multisensory integration, representation of emotions, motor control, and complex social processes such as empathy.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gogolla|first=Nadine|date=2017-06-19|title=The insular cortex|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0960982217305468|journal=Current Biology|language=en|volume=27|issue=12|pages=R580\u2013R586|doi=10.1016/j.cub.2017.05.010|issn=0960-9822}}</ref> Integration of sensory, emotional, and cognitive information allows for these diverse functions of the IC, so Gogolla sought to understand how this integration occurs and how it is aberrantly functioning in ASD models, both idiopathic and [[Genetic disorder|monogenic]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gogolla|first=Nadine|last2=Takesian|first2=Anne\u00a0E.|last3=Feng|first3=Guoping|last4=Fagiolini|first4=Michela|last5=Hensch|first5=Takao\u00a0K.|date=2014-08-20|title=Sensory Integration in Mouse Insular Cortex Reflects GABA Circuit Maturation|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0896627314005790|journal=Neuron|language=en|volume=83|issue=4|pages=894\u2013905|doi=10.1016/j.neuron.2014.06.033|issn=0896-6273}}</ref> Through in vivo fluorescence imaging techniques, Gogolla was able to record from the IC and observe multisensory integration emerging in the IC throughout early development, but this process did not occur in ASD models.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gogolla|first=Nadine|last2=Takesian|first2=Anne\u00a0E.|last3=Feng|first3=Guoping|last4=Fagiolini|first4=Michela|last5=Hensch|first5=Takao\u00a0K.|date=2014-08-20|title=Sensory Integration in Mouse Insular Cortex Reflects GABA Circuit Maturation|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0896627314005790|journal=Neuron|language=en|volume=83|issue=4|pages=894\u2013905|doi=10.1016/j.neuron.2014.06.033|issn=0896-6273}}</ref> She further found that expression of inhibitory neuron markers was decreased compared to controls in the IC of ASD mouse models suggesting that inhibitory/excitatory circuit balance is disrupted.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gogolla|first=Nadine|last2=Takesian|first2=Anne\u00a0E.|last3=Feng|first3=Guoping|last4=Fagiolini|first4=Michela|last5=Hensch|first5=Takao\u00a0K.|date=2014-08-20|title=Sensory Integration in Mouse Insular Cortex Reflects GABA Circuit Maturation|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0896627314005790|journal=Neuron|language=en|volume=83|issue=4|pages=894\u2013905|doi=10.1016/j.neuron.2014.06.033|issn=0896-6273}}</ref> Following this result, they pharmacologically enhanced inhibitory signalling in juvenile mice via systemic injections of [[diazepam]] for two weeks and found that it rescued integration deficits in ASD models.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gogolla|first=Nadine|last2=Takesian|first2=Anne\u00a0E.|last3=Feng|first3=Guoping|last4=Fagiolini|first4=Michela|last5=Hensch|first5=Takao\u00a0K.|date=2014-08-20|title=Sensory Integration in Mouse Insular Cortex Reflects GABA Circuit Maturation|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0896627314005790|journal=Neuron|language=en|volume=83|issue=4|pages=894\u2013905|doi=10.1016/j.neuron.2014.06.033|issn=0896-6273}}</ref> Intriguingly, enhancing inhibitory transmission pharmacologically in adult mice had no effect on neural circuit balance nor multisensory integration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.conte.harvard.edu/news/2014/8/1/rescuing-sensory-integration-in-mouse-models-of-autism|title=Rescuing sensory integration in mouse models of autism|website=Conte Center at Harvard|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> Their finding suggests that enhancing inhibitory transmission during a critical developmental period can restore inhibitory/excitatory balance and restore normal multisensory integration functions of the IC.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gogolla|first=Nadine|last2=Takesian|first2=Anne\u00a0E.|last3=Feng|first3=Guoping|last4=Fagiolini|first4=Michela|last5=Hensch|first5=Takao\u00a0K.|date=2014-08-20|title=Sensory Integration in Mouse Insular Cortex Reflects GABA Circuit Maturation|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0896627314005790|journal=Neuron|language=en|volume=83|issue=4|pages=894\u2013905|doi=10.1016/j.neuron.2014.06.033|issn=0896-6273}}</ref> Gogolla's research, published in Neuron in 2014, received a large amount of attention due to the new insights in provided in how ASD might manifest in the human brain and lead to ASD type behaviors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.harvard.edu/gazette/story/2014/07/help-for-halting-autism-symptoms/|title=Help for halting autism symptoms|date=2014-07-31|website=Harvard Gazette|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n== Career and Research  ==\nAfter finishing her posdoctoral work at Harvard, Gogolla moved back to Germany in 2013 where she started a faculty position at the [[Max Planck Institute of Neurobiology|Max Plank Institute of Neurobiology]] in Martinsried, Germany.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.harvard.edu/gazette/story/2014/07/help-for-halting-autism-symptoms/|title=Help for halting autism symptoms|date=2014-07-31|website=Harvard Gazette|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> Gogolla is also an Associate Faculty in the Graduate School of Systemic Neurosciences at the Munich Center for Neurosciences in the [[Ludwig Maximilian University of Munich|Ludwig-Maximilians-Universitat Munchen]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gsn.uni-muenchen.de/people/faculty/associate/gogolla/index.html|title=Dr. Nadine Gogolla|last=|first=|date=|website=Graduate School of Systemic Neuroscience - Munich Center for Neuroscience Brain and Mind|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> Gogolla currently leads a group of scientists at MPI where her research program focuses on exploring the neural circuits of the insular cortex as well as their connections to the prefrontal cortex and other limbic structures as a means to understand how it plays a part in so many diverse brain processes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.neuro.mpg.de/gogolla|title=Circuits for Emotion|website=www.neuro.mpg.de|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> A better understanding of the neural circuit mechanisms mediating diverse functions of the insular cortex, such as emotional regulation, empathy, and social behavior, will give insight into how processes are altered in disease states such as schizophrenia, ASD, addiction, and mood disorders.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.neuro.mpg.de/gogolla|title=Circuits for Emotion|website=www.neuro.mpg.de|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> To probe insular neural circuits, Gogolla and her lab use in vivo two-photon calcium imaging to record neural activity while mice are processing emotionally relevant stimuli, and they further use innovative behavioral assays, optogenetic techniques, and [[machine learning]] algorithms to link neural activity to behavior, manipulate neural circuits, and decode the activity of behaviorally and emotionally relevant IC neural ensembles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.neuro.mpg.de/gogolla|title=Circuits for Emotion|website=www.neuro.mpg.de|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> \n\nIn 2017, Gogolla wrote a review on the IC describing its anatomical location and connectivity, its role as an integration hub, its role in sensory processing, homeostatic regulation, emotional regulation, and valence processing as well as its role in driving behavior.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gogolla|first=Nadine|date=2017-06-19|title=The insular cortex|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0960982217305468|journal=Current Biology|language=en|volume=27|issue=12|pages=R580\u2013R586|doi=10.1016/j.cub.2017.05.010|issn=0960-9822}}</ref>  Gogolla also explored the human IC and how it is affected in different neurological and psychiatric disorders to emphasize the importance of gaining a better understanding of this region, an integral goal of her research program.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gogolla|first=Nadine|date=2017-06-19|title=The insular cortex|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0960982217305468|journal=Current Biology|language=en|volume=27|issue=12|pages=R580\u2013R586|doi=10.1016/j.cub.2017.05.010|issn=0960-9822}}</ref> \n\nIn 2019, Gogolla described role of the posterior insular cortex (pIC) to central amygdala projection in the mediating anxiety-related behaviors as well as the posterior insular cortex to nucleus accumbens projection in the inhibition of feeding behaviors.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gehrlach|first=Daniel A.|last2=Dolensek|first2=Nejc|last3=Klein|first3=Alexandra S.|last4=Roy Chowdhury|first4=Ritu|last5=Matthys|first5=Arthur|last6=Jungh\u00e4nel|first6=Michaela|last7=Gaitanos|first7=Thomas N.|last8=Podgornik|first8=Alja|last9=Black|first9=Thomas D.|last10=Reddy Vaka|first10=Narasimha|last11=Conzelmann|first11=Karl-Klaus|date=September 2019|title=Aversive state processing in the posterior insular cortex|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/s41593-019-0469-1|journal=Nature Neuroscience|language=en|volume=22|issue=9|pages=1424\u20131437|doi=10.1038/s41593-019-0469-1|issn=1546-1726}}</ref> Using [[optogenetics]], they found that stimulating the pIC caused aversive behaviors as well as increased autonomic responses.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gehrlach|first=Daniel A.|last2=Dolensek|first2=Nejc|last3=Klein|first3=Alexandra S.|last4=Roy Chowdhury|first4=Ritu|last5=Matthys|first5=Arthur|last6=Jungh\u00e4nel|first6=Michaela|last7=Gaitanos|first7=Thomas N.|last8=Podgornik|first8=Alja|last9=Black|first9=Thomas D.|last10=Reddy Vaka|first10=Narasimha|last11=Conzelmann|first11=Karl-Klaus|date=September 2019|title=Aversive state processing in the posterior insular cortex|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/s41593-019-0469-1|journal=Nature Neuroscience|language=en|volume=22|issue=9|pages=1424\u20131437|doi=10.1038/s41593-019-0469-1|issn=1546-1726}}</ref> Then, using in vivo [[Two-photon excitation microscopy|two-photon calcium imaging]], Gogolla and her team were able to record calcium transients in neurons in the pIC as an indicator of neural activity to establish a causal relationship between pIC activity and the convergence and integration of acute sensory stimuli as well as sustained affective and homeostatic states.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gehrlach|first=Daniel A.|last2=Dolensek|first2=Nejc|last3=Klein|first3=Alexandra S.|last4=Roy Chowdhury|first4=Ritu|last5=Matthys|first5=Arthur|last6=Jungh\u00e4nel|first6=Michaela|last7=Gaitanos|first7=Thomas N.|last8=Podgornik|first8=Alja|last9=Black|first9=Thomas D.|last10=Reddy Vaka|first10=Narasimha|last11=Conzelmann|first11=Karl-Klaus|date=September 2019|title=Aversive state processing in the posterior insular cortex|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/s41593-019-0469-1|journal=Nature Neuroscience|language=en|volume=22|issue=9|pages=1424\u20131437|doi=10.1038/s41593-019-0469-1|issn=1546-1726}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, Gogolla and her team published a groundbreaking paper using innovative machine learning and two-photon technologies to show that mouse facial expressions correlate with internal emotional states and that neural activity in the IC is closely correlated with specific facial expressions in mice.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dolensek|first=Nejc|last2=Gehrlach|first2=Daniel A.|last3=Klein|first3=Alexandra S.|last4=Gogolla|first4=Nadine|date=2020-04-03|title=Facial expressions of emotion states and their neuronal correlates in mice|url=https://science.sciencemag.org/content/368/6486/89|journal=Science|language=en|volume=368|issue=6486|pages=89\u201394|doi=10.1126/science.aaz9468|issn=0036-8075|pmid=32241948}}</ref> Gogolla was inspired by a 2014 Cell paper stating that emotions represent brain states and should last for a discrete amount of time after the stimulus that evoked them and, importantly, they should scale to the  strength of the stimulus that evoked them.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Abbott|first=Alison|date=2020-04-02|title=Artificial intelligence decodes the facial expressions of mice|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-020-01002-7|journal=Nature|language=en|doi=10.1038/d41586-020-01002-7}}</ref> As such, Gogolla presented salient stimuli to headfixed mice, such as sweet and bitter tastes or slightly painful shocks, meant to trigger specific emotional responses.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Abbott|first=Alison|date=2020-04-02|title=Artificial intelligence decodes the facial expressions of mice|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-020-01002-7|journal=Nature|language=en|doi=10.1038/d41586-020-01002-7}}</ref> While they presented these stimuli, they recorded the faces of the mice and then broke down the video recordings into facial-muscle movements that they then used to train a machine learning algorithm to detect distinct facial-muscle movements that correlate with emotions.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Abbott|first=Alison|date=2020-04-02|title=Artificial intelligence decodes the facial expressions of mice|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-020-01002-7|journal=Nature|language=en|doi=10.1038/d41586-020-01002-7}}</ref> For example, they found that when a mouse experiences pain, its nose drooped and its ears tilted downward.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/02/world/mice-facial-expressions-scn-trnd/index.html|title=Mice make different faces depending on how they feel -- and that could impact how we treat mood disorders, a new study says|first=Scottie |last=Andrew|website=CNN|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> Not only was the algorithm able to detect distinct facial expressions that correlated to the distinct emotion-evoking stimuli, but the facial expressions were also graded based on the intensity of the stimulus presented.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Abbott|first=Alison|date=2020-04-02|title=Artificial intelligence decodes the facial expressions of mice|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-020-01002-7|journal=Nature|language=en|doi=10.1038/d41586-020-01002-7}}</ref> This unbiased and quantitative approach to recognizing facial expressions, and thus emotional state readouts, will finally allow neuroscientists to ask and answer questions about how the brain processes emotion and drives motivated behaviors.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dolensek|first=Nejc|last2=Gehrlach|first2=Daniel A.|last3=Klein|first3=Alexandra S.|last4=Gogolla|first4=Nadine|date=2020-04-03|title=Facial expressions of emotion states and their neuronal correlates in mice|url=https://science.sciencemag.org/content/368/6486/89|journal=Science|language=en|volume=368|issue=6486|pages=89\u201394|doi=10.1126/science.aaz9468|issn=0036-8075|pmid=32241948}}</ref> The second part of the study focused on the neural basis of these facial expressions, or emotional states. Gogolla's team recorded neurons in the IC using two-photon imaging such that they could observe neurons with single-cell resolution to observe neurons that only fire when particular facial expressions are performed.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Abbott|first=Alison|date=2020-04-02|title=Artificial intelligence decodes the facial expressions of mice|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-020-01002-7|journal=Nature|language=en|doi=10.1038/d41586-020-01002-7}}</ref> Further, they used [[optogenetics]] to drive specific neural circuits known to be involved in specific emotional states and trigger the corresponding facial expressions in mice.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Abbott|first=Alison|date=2020-04-02|title=Artificial intelligence decodes the facial expressions of mice|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-020-01002-7|journal=Nature|language=en|doi=10.1038/d41586-020-01002-7}}</ref> This study emphasizes the power of applying machine learning techniques to neuroscience questions since the faces of animals may have appeared to be emotionless to human observers but machine learning algorithms were able to detect the subtle changes that indicate distinct emotional states.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2020/04/200402144430.htm|title=The facial expressions of mice: The face of a mouse reveals its emotions|website=ScienceDaily|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> These findings have dramatically improved our ability to dissect how and where emotions arise in the brain, now that we can detect and quantify them in animal models, which opens up the potential to translate these findings to the human brain to understand brain disorders characterized by aberrations in emotional processing and emotional regulation such as mood disorders.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/02/world/mice-facial-expressions-scn-trnd/index.html|title=Mice make different faces depending on how they feel -- and that could impact how we treat mood disorders, a new study says|first=Scottie |last=Andrew|website=CNN|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and Honors ==\n\n* '''2017''': ERC Starting Grant \"Insular Anxiety\"<ref name=\"neuro.mpg.de\"/>\n* '''2011 \u2013 2013:''' Charles A. King Trust, Post-doctoral Research Fellowship Award<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hria.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/King_Basic_Grant_Recipients_2003-2019.pdf|title=Charles A. King Trust Postdoctoral Fellowship Program Basic Science|last=|first=|date=|website=King Basic Grant Recipients|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 5, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.conte.harvard.edu/news/2014/8/1/rescuing-sensory-integration-in-mouse-models-of-autism|title=Rescuing sensory integration in mouse models of autism|website=Conte Center at Harvard|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n* '''2008 \u2013 2011:''' Human Frontiers Science Program (HFSP) Long-Term Fellowship<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hfsp.org/awardees/awards?field_countries_target_id&field_nationalities_target_id&field_award_type_target_id=All&page=115|title=Awards {{!}} Human Frontier Science Program|website=www.hfsp.org|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n* '''2008 \u2013 2011:''' Jane Coffin Childs Memorial Fund for Medical Research \u2013 Long-Term Fellowship (declined in favor of HFSP Award)<ref name=\"neuro.mpg.de\"/>\n* '''2008:''' Ed Fisher Prize, Best Ph.D. Thesis Award, Friedrich Miescher Institute, Basel<ref name=\"neuro.mpg.de\"/>\n* '''1997 - 2002''': German National Academic Merit Foundation (Studienstiftung des Deutschen Volkes), full scholarship<ref name=\"neuro.mpg.de\"/>\n\n==Selected publications==\n*Dolensek, N., Gehrlach, D. A., Klein, A. S. & '''Gogolla''', N. ''Science'' <nowiki>https://www.doi.org/10.1126/science.aaz9468</nowiki> (2020).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dolensek|first=Nejc|last2=Gehrlach|first2=Daniel A.|last3=Klein|first3=Alexandra S.|last4=Gogolla|first4=Nadine|date=2020-04-03|title=Facial expressions of emotion states and their neuronal correlates in mice|url=https://science.sciencemag.org/content/368/6486/89|journal=Science|language=en|volume=368|issue=6486|pages=89\u201394|doi=10.1126/science.aaz9468|issn=0036-8075|pmid=32241948}}</ref>\n*{{Cite journal|\nlast=Gehrlach|first=D.A.|\nlast2=Dolensek|first2=N.|\nlast3=Klein|first3=A.S.|\nlast4=Roy Chowdhury|first4=R.|\nlast5=Matthys|first5=A.|\nlast6=Jungh\u00e4nel|first6=M.|\nlast7=Gaitanos|first7=T.N.|\nlast8=Podgornik|first8=A.|\nlast9=Black|first9=T.D.|\nlast10=Reddy Vaka|first10=N.|\nlast11=Conzelmann|first11=K.-K.|\nlast12='''Gogolla'''|first12=N.|\ndate=2019-08-27|\ntitle=Aversive state processing in the posterior insular cortex|\njournal=Nature Neuroscience|\nvolume=22|\nissue=9|\npages=1424\u20131437|\ndoi=10.1038/s41593-019-0469-1|\npmid=31455886}}\n*'''Gogolla N''' (2017). The insular cortex. Curr Biol 27: R580-R586 (2017).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gogolla|first=Nadine|date=2017-06-19|title=The insular cortex|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0960982217305468|journal=Current Biology|language=en|volume=27|issue=12|pages=R580\u2013R586|doi=10.1016/j.cub.2017.05.010|issn=0960-9822}}</ref>\n*{{Cite journal|\nlast='''Gogolla'''|first=N.|\nlast2=Takesian|first2=A.E.|\nlast3=Feng|first3=G.|\nlast4=Fagiolini|first4=M.|\nlast5=Hensch|first5=T.K.|\ndate=2014-08-20|\ntitle=Sensory Integration in Mouse Insular Cortex Reflects GABA Circuit Maturation|\njournal=Neuron|\nvolume=83|\nissue=4|\npages=894\u2013905|\ndoi=10.1016/j.neuron.2014.06.033|\npmid=25088363}}\n*{{Cite journal|\nlast='''Gogolla'''|first=N.|\nlast2=Caroni|first2=P.|\nlast3=Luthi|first3=A.|\nlast4=Herry|first4=C.|\ndate=2009-09-04|\ntitle=Perineuronal nets protect fear memories from erasure|\njournal=Science|\nvolume=325|\nissue=5945|\npages=1258\u20131261|\ndoi=10.1126/science.1174146|\npmid=19729657}}\n*{{Cite journal|\nlast='''Gogolla'''|first=N.|\nlast2=LeBlanc|first2=J.J.|\nlast3=Quast|first3=K.B.|\nlast4=S\u00fcdhof|first4=T.C.|\nlast5=Fagiolini|first5=M.|\nlast6=Hensch|first6=T.K.|\ndate=2009-06-04|\ntitle=Perineuronal nets protect fear memories from erasure|\njournal=Journal of Neurodevelopmental Disorders|\nvolume=1|\nissue=2|\npages=172\u2013181|\ndoi=10.1007/s11689-009-9023-x|\npmid=20664807}}\n*'''Gogolla N'''*, LeBlanc JJ*, Quast KB*, S\u00fcdhof TC, Fagiolini M, Hensch TK (2009). Common circuit defect of excitatory-inhibitory balance in mouse models of autism. J Neurodev Disorders 1: 172-181.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gogolla|first=Nadine|last2=Leblanc|first2=Jocelyn J.|last3=Quast|first3=Kathleen B.|last4=S\u00fcdhof|first4=Thomas C.|last5=Fagiolini|first5=Michela|last6=Hensch|first6=Takao K.|date=2009-06|title=Common circuit defect of excitatory-inhibitory balance in mouse models of autism|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20664807|journal=Journal of Neurodevelopmental Disorders|volume=1|issue=2|pages=172\u2013181|doi=10.1007/s11689-009-9023-x|issn=1866-1955|pmc=2906812|pmid=20664807}}</ref>\n*'''Gogolla N''', Galimberti I, Deguchi Y, Caroni P (2009). Wnt signaling mediates experience-related regulation of synapse numbers and mossy fiber connectivities in the adult hippocampus. Neuron 62: 510-525.<ref>{{Cite we