g/wiki/Nadine_Gogolla"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Delaware", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing pandemic in Delaware, United States}}\n{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Delaware\n| map1            = Number of COVID 19 cases in Delaware.svg\n| legend1         = Counties by number of positive cases in Delaware as of March 27:{{legend|#510000|100+ Confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#900000|50-99 Confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#c80200|25-49 Confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#ee7070|10-24 Confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#ffC0C0|1\u20139 Confirmed cases}}\n| first_case      = [[New Castle County]]\n| arrival_date    = March 11, 2020\n| confirmed_cases = 783\n| recovery_cases  = 71\n| deaths          = 15\n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Delaware]], U.S.\n| website         = [https://www.dhss.delaware.gov/dhss/dph/epi/2019novelcoronavirus.html Delaware Department of Health and Social Services]\n}}\n\nThe '''[[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]''' was reported to have reached the [[U.S. state]] of '''[[Delaware]]''' on March 11, 2020 in [[New Castle County]]. As of April 6, 2020, the [[Delaware Department of Health and Social Services]] has confirmed 783 positive cases and 15 deaths in Delaware, with 71 people being fully recovered.\n\n== Timeline ==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Delaware medical cases chart}}\n\n=== March 4 ===\n\nOn March 4, in preparation for the coronavirus' spread in Delaware, the [[Delaware Division of Public Health]] opened a coronavirus call center at its State Health Operation Center in [[Smyrna, Delaware|Smyrna]] to assist with questions that businesses, schools, and people may have about the disease.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wboc.com/story/41853374/delaware-division-of-public-health-opens-coronavirus-call-center|title=Delaware Opens Coronavirus Call Center|website=wboc.com|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\n=== March 11\u201313 ===\nOn March 11, the Delaware Division of Public Health announced its first presumptive positive case of coronavirus in Delaware. The positive case involved a man over the age of 50 in [[New Castle County, Delaware|New Castle County]] who was associated with the [[University of Delaware]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.delaware.gov/2020/03/11/public-health-announces-first-presumptive-positive-case-of-coronavirus-in-delaware-resident/|title=Public Health Announces First Presumptive Positive Case of Coronavirus in Delaware Resident|date=2020-03-11|website=State of Delaware News|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, Delaware Governor [[John Carney (politician)|John Carney]] declared a state of emergency. This allowed for the [[Delaware National Guard]] to take precautionary actions and prepare for further response to the disease, for the state to conduct public meetings electronically, and prevent the price gouging of goods. Governor Carney also recommended that all non-essential public gatherings of over 100 people be cancelled, following CDC guidelines.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.wboc.com/story/41888267/governor-carney-declares-state-of-emergency-amidst-coronavirus-outbreak|title=Governor Carney Declares State of Emergency Amidst Coronavirus Outbreak|last=Lu|first=Amy|website=wboc.com|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> Three more positive cases of coronavirus were confirmed on March 12. The patients were two graduate students and a postdoctoral researcher at the University of Delaware.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://philadelphia.cbslocal.com/2020/03/12/coronavirus-university-of-delaware-announces-3-more-members-test-positive-coronavirus-professor-diagnosed/|title=Coronavirus In Delaware: Governor Declares State Of Emergency As 3 More University Of Delaware Members Test Positive For COVID-19|date=2020-03-12|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> [[Delaware State University]] President Dr. Tony Allen advised all students to not return to campus until at least April 5. He also announced that all classes from March 18 until April 5 will take place online.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.desu.edu/student-life/student-health-services/coronavirus|title=Coronavirus|date=2020-03-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315023946/https://www.desu.edu/student-life/student-health-services/coronavirus|access-date=2020-03-15|archive-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, the Downtown Dover Partnership announced the cancellation of the [[Saint Patrick's Day|St. Patrick's Day]] parade due to coronavirus concerns.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.wboc.com/story/41892567/dover-cancels-permits-for-large-events-in-light-of-covid19-state-of-emergency|title=Dover Cancels Permits for Large Events in Light of COVID-19 State of Emergency|last=Lehman|first=Tom|website=wboc.com|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> Late on March 13, Governor Carney closed all Delaware Public Schools from March 16 to March 27.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.wboc.com/story/41896010/delaware-schools-on-hiatus-for-two-weeks-due-to-covid19|title=Delaware Schools on Hiatus for Two Weeks Due to COVID-19|last=Semyon|first=Cassandra|website=wboc.com|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> In addition, the University of Delaware announced that all classes after spring break would be moved to an all-online format for the remainder of the semester. All University of Delaware on-campus housing would close for students who remained on the campus during spring break on March 17 at 10:00 pm and for all students who were returning to campus on March 22 at 10:00 pm.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.udel.edu/udaily/2020/march/coronavirus-update-march-13-2020/|title=March 13 Coronavirus update: residence halls to close {{!}} UDaily|website=udel.edu|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\n=== March 14\u201316 ===\nOn March 14, the Delaware Division of Public Health announced two more positive cases of coronavirus in the state. The two new patients were both self-quarantining in New Castle County: a woman older than 50 and a man older than 60. This increased the number of total positive cases in Delaware to 6.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wboc.com/story/41895944/dph-announces-2-more-likely-cases-of-covid19-in-delaware|title=DPH Announces 2 More Likely Positive Cases of COVID-19 in Delaware|website=wboc.com|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\nDelaware announced their seventh case in the state on March 15; the case is associated with University of Delaware.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://6abc.com/6015929/|title=7th coronavirus case confirmed in Delaware|date=2020-03-15|website=6abc Philadelphia|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\nThe Delaware Division of Public Health announced on March 16 that a woman over 50 in New Castle County was confirmed to have coronavirus. The number of total number of positive cases increased to 8 in Delaware with the addition of this case.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wmdt.com/2020/03/just-in-eighth-positive-coronavirus-case-confirmed-in-delaware-dph-says/|title=JUST IN: Eighth positive coronavirus case confirmed in Delaware, DPH says|date=2020-03-16|website=47abc|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\n=== March 17\u201319 ===\nIt was announced on March 17 that eight additional positive cases of coronavirus were confirmed in the state, including the first in [[Sussex County, Delaware|Sussex County]]. Of the patients, four were men and four were women, though their ages have not been revealed. This increased the total number of positive cases to 16 in Delaware.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wboc.com/story/41906635/first-covid19-case-in-sussex-county-reported-state-cases-double|title=First COVID-19 Case in Sussex County Reported, State Cases Double|website=wboc.com|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref>\n\nOn March 18, the DDHS announced the addition of 10 more positive cases in the state of Delaware, including the first three in [[Kent County, Delaware|Kent County]]. All three of Delaware's counties had at least one coronavirus case by March 18. The addition of these cases increased the cumulative number of positive cases to 26 for the state.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wboc.com/story/41909829/first-coronavirus-case-reported-in-kent-county-del|title=UPDATE: Delaware COVID-19 Cases Rise to 26, Kent and Sussex Record 3 Positive Tests Each|website=wboc.com|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\n[[Dover Air Force Base]] declared a public health emergency on March 18, allowing for tighter restrictions of the movement of people on the base, including personnel restrictions and access restrictions to the base's installation. In addition, the emergency allowed the isolation and quarantine procedures for the base to go into effect.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wboc.com/story/41909048/dover-air-force-base-declares-public-health-emergency|title=Dover Air Force Base Declares Public Health Emergency|last=Kerr|first=Rose|website=wboc.com|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\nOn March 19, the number of cases was confirmed to have increased to 30: 23 in New Castle, 3 in Sussex, and 4 in Kent Counties.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wmdt.com/2020/03/four-additional-cases-announced-in-delaware/|title=Four additional cases announced in Delaware|date=2020-03-19|website=47abc|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\n=== March 20\u201322 ===\n\nOn March 20, the state reported 27 lab-confirmed cases of COVID-19 in New Castle County, five in Kent County and seven in Sussex County, which brings the total to 39, with two people being in critical condition.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nThe Delaware Division of Public Health (DPH) had reported 30 COVID-19 cases in the state just the day before. DPH said testing is recommended for people with a fever and either a cough or shortness of breath.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wboc.com/story/41921160/first-coronavirus-case-reported-in-kent-county-del|title=Delaware COVID-19 Cases Rise to 38|website=wboc.com|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\n== Government response ==\n\n==== March 12 ====\nDelaware Governor John Carney declared a state of emergency on March 12, allowing for the Delaware National Guard to prepare for the coronavirus' spread.<ref name=\":1\" /> He would close all public schools in the state on March 13.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==== March 13 ====\nThe City of Dover canceled all permits for event gatherings of over 100 people on March 13, citing the governor's recommendation.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==== March 23 ====\n\nOn March 23, Governor John Carney has issued the [[stay-at-home order]] to stop the spread of COVID-19. All non-essential businesses have been ordered to close. Governor Carney issued the order Sunday night, set to go in effect Tuesday morning at 8 a.m., stating \"All non-essential businesses are closed. All Delawareans are instructed to stay in their homes, except when they are going to and from their place of business if it's permitted to stay open\". This shelter-in-place order will remain in effect until May 15.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wboc.com/story/41929980/delaware-prepares-for-stay-at-home-order|title=Delaware Prepares for Stay at Home Order|last=Semyon|first=Cassandra|website=wboc.com|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Additionally, Delaware schools are to remain closed through May 15 to fight the spread of COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wboc.com/story/41930078/delaware-schools-to-remain-closed-through-may-15-to-fight-spread-of-covid19|title=Delaware Schools to Remain Closed Through May 15 to Fight Spread of COVID-19|last=Lehman|first=Tom|website=wboc.com|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n==Impact on sports==\nIn college sports, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] cancelled all winter and spring tournaments, most notably the [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men]]'s and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women]]'s basketball tournaments, affecting colleges and universities statewide.<ref name=ncaa>[https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships] NCAA, March 12, 2020</ref> On March 16, the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] also canceled the remainder of the winter seasons as well as the spring seasons.<ref>[https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html NJCAA cancels spring sports, basketball nationals amid coronavirus outbreak] MLive.com, March 16, 2020</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n! colspan=\"2\" |2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) Cases in Delaware<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dhss.delaware.gov/dhss/dph/epi/2019novelcoronavirus.html|title=2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) - Delaware Health and Social Services - State of Delaware|website=dhss.delaware.gov|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\nUpdated April 4, 2020\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |County\n! scope=\"col\" |Confirmed Cases\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |New Castle\n|400\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Kent\n|68\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Sussex\n|125\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |Total\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |593\n|}\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.dhss.delaware.gov/dhss/dph/epi/2019novelcoronavirus.html Coronavirus information] from the Delaware Department of Health and Social Services\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Medicine|United States|Viruses|Coronavirus disease 2019|Pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by state|Delaware]]\n[[Category:2020 in Delaware]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Delaware]]\n[[Category:Health in Delaware]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronaviru